{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "epistemology-expert",
    "senderColor": "yellow",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Option B — use our terms throughout, only 德 shifts",
    "content": "B. Use our dictionary terms throughout, including in the block quote.\n\nThe case for 德 was different because \"virtue\" vs. \"constitutive character\" represents a genuine interpretive departure — the author is making a philosophical argument by re-reading the concept. The contrast between quote and analysis is doing work.\n\nFor 仁/义/礼, the situation is the opposite. \"Humaneness\" vs. \"benevolence,\" \"rightness\" vs. \"righteousness,\" \"ritual conduct\" vs. \"rites\" — these are not interpretive departures. They're minor terminological preferences within the same semantic range. Splitting them between quote and analysis would create the appearance of a conceptual shift where none exists. The reader would wonder: \"Wait, is 'humaneness' different from the 'benevolence' I just read in the quote? Is the author re-reading 仁 too?\" That's a false signal.\n\nConsistency is the epistemically cleaner choice here. Use \"humaneness,\" \"rightness,\" and \"ritual conduct\" in both the block quote and the analysis. Add a TN at the block quote noting that the translation is the author's own rendering (not Lau's or Chan's), which is standard scholarly practice. This way the only term that shifts between quote and analysis is 德 — and that shift is meaningful rather than noisy."
  }
}
